# Semantic Commit Messages

Use semantic commit messages for all commits and PR titles.

## Format

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>
```

- `<scope>` is **optional**. If a change is specific to one or two packages/areas, add the scope. Keep scopes brief but recognizable (e.g. `core`, `lobby`, `loading`, `assets`, `ui`).
- `<subject>` is a summary in **present tense, lower case** (not title case), with no trailing period.

## Types

- `feat`: a new API or behavior for the end user.
- `fix`: a bug fix for the end user.
- `docs`: a change to docs or other Markdown documents in the repo.
- `refactor`: a change to production code with no behavior difference (splitting files, renaming internal variables, improving code style…).
- `test`: adding missing tests or refactoring tests; no production code change.
- `chore`: upgrading dependencies, releasing new versions, and other regular maintenance.
- `misc`: anything else that doesn't change production code, yet is not `test` or `chore` (e.g. updating CI workflow).

## Example

```
feat(core): allow overriding of webpack config
^--^^----^  ^------------^
|   |       |
|   |       +-> Summary in present tense. Use lower case not title case!
|   |
|   +-> The package(s) that this change affected.
|
+-------> Type: see above for the list we use.
```

## Notes

- PRs are squash-merged, so the PR title becomes the commit on `main` — name PR titles semantically. Individual commits within a branch don't need to be strictly semantic.
- Conventions matter less than correct code; don't over-stress the title.
